Hello Scroll down for English
 
The TRUEx96 CPU architecture is an extremely simple CPU designed entirely by myself
(It may not technically be a CPU)
I have not taken any professional courses in digital circuits
I just came up with it out of boredom during classes.
This work is open-source, commercial use prohibited.
 
Instruction format:
Operand [5 bits] + Opcode [3 bits]
 
Instruction set as follows:
 
xxxxx 000  Immediate value
00xxx 001  ALU operation
xxxxx 010  Move xxxxx register to REG_I (buffer register, not counted in general registers, 16 bits)
xxxxx 011  Move REG_I to xxxxx register
0000x 100  JE (Jump if equal/condition)
00000 101  JMP (Unconditional jump)
xxxxx 110  Move IN from address xxxxx to REG_5 (16-bit; all IN data go to 16-bit REG_5)
xxxxx 111  Move value from REG_4 to OUT at address xxxxx (similar to above)
 
Immediate value:
Max immediate value = 32
 
ALU operations:
Operate on REG_1 and REG_2, result to REG_3
Supports: add, sub, nand, or, and, not
 
add  00 000 001
sub  00 001 001
and  00 010 001
or   00 011 001
not  00 100 001
 
JE:
Check REG_2 for =0 or >0
Jump address stored in REG_0
 
=0   00 00 0 100
>0   00 00 1 100
 
JMP:
Unconditional jump
Jump address stored in REG_0
 
What? You say there’s no HALT command? Hahaha, of course there is.
 
When an immediate value of 0 appears, a counter increments automatically.
If it is 0 again the second time (check opcode and REG_0),
and this happens 5 times total, the CPU halts.
